   <text>
      <body>
         <div type="letter">
            <pb n="1" facs="Edgeworth_Huntington_FB1235_1817-06-09_page01.jpg"/>
            <opener>
               <dateline>
                  <placeName ref="./Placeography.xml#Edgeworthstown_IE">Edgeworths town</placeName>
                  <lb/>
                  <date when="1817-06-09">June 9<hi rend="superscript">th</hi>. 1817</date>
               </dateline>
               <salute>
   Sir<lb/>
               </salute>
            </opener>
            <p>With the proud, I hope<lb/>
               not absolutely <choice>
                  <orig>presump<lb/>
                  -tious</orig>
                  <reg>presumptious</reg>
               </choice> hope, that you do<lb/>
               not quite forget the <choice>
                  <orig>fami-<lb/>
                  ly</orig>
                  <reg/>
               </choice> of Edgeworth who had<lb/>
               the honor of being <choice>
                  <orig>distin<lb/>
                  -guished</orig>
                  <reg>distinguished</reg>
               </choice> by you, &amp; the<lb/>
               pleasure of enjoying your<lb/>
               conversation at <placeName ref="./Placeography.xml#Paris_FR">Paris</placeName> in<lb/>
               the year 1803, I venture<lb/>
               now to present to you <persName ref="./Personography.xml#EdgeF2">M<hi rend="superscript">rs</hi>.-<lb/>
                  Edgeworth</persName>'s brother <persName ref="./Personography.xml#BeauF1">Capt<hi rend="superscript">n</hi>.-<lb/>
                  Beaufort</persName> of the Royal <choice>
                  <orig>Na<lb/>
               -vy</orig>
                  <reg>Navy</reg>
               </choice> - a gentleman whose<lb/>
               <title ref="./Workography.xml#Karam1">survey and account</title> of<lb/>
               the coast of <placeName ref="./Placeography.xml#Karaman_TR">Karamania</placeName>
               <lb/>
               just published may be<lb/>
               <pb n="2" facs="Edgeworth_Huntington_FB1235_1817-06-09_page02.jpg"/>
               
               known to you. If you are<lb/>
               so good as to honor him<lb/>
               with even ten minutes<lb/>
               of your conversation I trust<lb/>
               securely to your penetration<lb/>
               for discovering that I do<lb/>
               not present to you an <choice>
                  <orig>un-<lb/>
                  -interesting</orig>
                  <reg>uninteresting</reg>
               </choice> stranger -<lb/></p>
               
               <p>Is there any chance of<lb/>
               your visiting <placeName ref="./Placeography.xml#IE">Ireland</placeName>? -<lb/>
               - To see the <placeName ref="./Placeography.xml#Dunsink_IE">Observatory of<lb/>
               Dublin</placeName> &amp; the celebrated<lb/>
               astronomer <persName ref="./Personography.xml#BrinJ1">D<hi rend="superscript">r</hi>. Brinkley</persName>
               <lb/>
               or to see the giants <choice>
                  <orig>cause<lb/>
                  -way</orig>
                  <reg>causeway</reg>
               </choice> &amp; the geological<lb/>
               wonders of this country<lb/>
               might possibly tempt you<lb/>
               here - all that I can ask<lb/>
               is that you would write<lb/>
               a line to let me know<lb/>
               <pb n="3" facs="Edgeworth_Huntington_FB1235_1817-06-09_page03.jpg"/>
               
               whether you have any such<lb/>
               intentions - &amp; when -<lb/>
               <persName ref="./Personography.xml#EdgeR1">My father</persName> is at this <choice>
                  <orig>mo-<lb/>
                  ment</orig>
                  <reg>moment</reg>
               </choice> very ill - But his<lb/>
               mind retains all its<lb/>
               intellectual vigor, and<lb/>
               taste for science &amp; <choice>
                  <orig>litera-<lb/>
                  -ture</orig>
                  <reg>literature</reg>
               </choice> - and I have a brother<lb/>
               who has the highest <choice>
                  <orig>am-<lb/>
                  bition</orig>
                  <reg>ambition</reg>
               </choice> to be known to<lb/>
               you - and whose tastes<lb/>
               &amp; if I may say so, talents<lb/>
               are deserving of that<lb/>
               honor.<lb/></p>
               <p><persName ref="./Personography.xml#EdgeR1">My father</persName> &amp; <persName ref="./Personography.xml#EdgeF2">M<hi rend="superscript">rs</hi>. Edgeworth</persName>
               <lb/>
               desire their respectful<lb/>
               remembrances<lb/>
            </p>
            <closer>
               I have the honor to be<lb/>
               Sir<lb/>
               with high esteem<lb/>
               your obed<hi rend="superscript">t</hi> servant<lb/>
               <persName ref="./Personography.xml#EdgeM1">Maria Edgeworth</persName>
               <lb/>
               <pb n="4" facs="Edgeworth_Huntington_FB1235_1817-06-09_page04.jpg"/>
               <address>
                  <addrLine>A</addrLine>
                  <addrLine>Monsieur</addrLine>
                  <addrLine><persName ref="./Personography.xml#BiotJ1">Monsieur Biot.</persName></addrLine>
               </address>
            </closer>
